Development of the JNK MAPK Signaling Pathway Assay

To complement the p38 MAPK assay described elsewhere (Trask et al., 2006; Williams et al., 2006), we set out to develop a c‚ÄêJun activation assay leveraging a similar HCS approach. The c‚ÄêJun activation assay was developed in the HeLa adenocarcinoma cervical cell line (ATCC‚ÄêCCL2) using a commercially available screening kit (Hitkit) purchased from Cellomics. To conÔ¨Årm that the SAPK signaling pathway is intact in the HeLa cell line, cells are either left untreated or are treated with 100 nM of the protein synthesis inhibitor anisomycin for 30 min. Cells are then solubilized in SDS sample buffer, their total cellular proteins are separated on 10% SDS‚Äê PAGE gels, transferred to nitrocellulose, and the resulting blots are probed with speciÔ¨Åc antibodies for the total and phosphorylated forms of JNK1, JNK2, and c‚ÄêJun (Fig. 1A). The total JNK1, JNK2, and c‚ÄêJun signals detected on the Western blots appear unaffected by anisomycin treatment. However, activation of the JNK/SAPK signaling pathway by anisomycin treatment dramatically increases the phosphorylation signals for JNK1, JNK2, and c‚ÄêJun relative to untreated controls (Fig. 1A). The c‚ÄêJun activation kit from Cellomics utilizes a combination of a primary mouse monoclonal antibody to phospho‚Äêc‚ÄêJun (Ser 63) and an Alexa 488‚Äêconjugated goat anti‚Äêmouse IgG secondary antibody to measure the amount of phospho‚Äêc‚ÄêJun in cells by indirect immunoÔ¨Çuorescence. HeLa cells (5 √Ç 103) per well were seeded in EMEM √æ 10% fetal bovine serum (FBS) and 2 mM L‚Äêglutamine and were incubated overnight at 37 and 5% CO2. Medium, with or without 100 nM anisomycin, was added and the plates were incubated at 37 and 5% CO2 for 25 min. The cells were Ô¨Åxed with formaldehyde, permeabilized, incubated with the primary mouse antibody against phoshorylated c‚ÄêJun, washed, and then incubated with the goat anti‚Äêmouse secondary antibody conjugated with Alexa Fluor 488 containing Hoechst dye. The Cellomics ArrayScan 3.1 is used to capture images of the phospho‚Äêc‚ÄêJun in Ô¨Åelds of view of untreated and anisomycin‚Äêtreated HeLa cells (Fig. 1B). The level of phospho‚Äêc‚ÄêJun Ô¨Çuorescent signal is signiÔ¨Åcantly brighter in anisomycin‚Äêtreated cells than in untreated cells, and the majority of the staining of both populations appears localized within the nucleus. Labeling nuclei with Hoechst 33342 identiÔ¨Åes the nuclear region, and this signal is used to focus the instrument and in deÔ¨Åning a nuclear mask. The cytoplasm‚Äêto‚Äênuclear translocation algorithm measures the relative distribution of the target, in this case c‚ÄêJun, between two cellular compartments, the cytoplasm and the nucleus. Bit maps of individual cells, from both nuclear and c‚ÄêJun channels for untreated and treated cells, are also shown (Fig. 1B). As determined by the algorithm, the nuclear masks are indicated in blue and the cytoplasmic ring masks are indicated in green. While the

