407

Protocol 1. Harvest HeLa cells and seed 5000 cells per well into 96‚Äêwell plate(s) in medium. 2. Culture cells at 37 , 5% CO2 overnight. 3. Add 25 l of compound (inhibitor) to the wells and incubate for 15 min at 37 , 5% CO2. 4. Add 25 l of 10 ng/ml OSM activation stimulus to the wells and incubate for 10 min at 37 , 5% CO2. 5. Aspirate medium and add 100 l of prewarmed Ô¨Åxation solution (3.7% formalin) and incubate for 10 min at room temperature. 6. Wash once with 100 l wash buffer, aspirate wash buffer, add 100 l of permeabilization buffer, and incubate for 90 s. 7. Aspirate permeabilization buffer and add 100 l wash buffer. 8. Aspirate buffer and add 50 l of primary antibody; 1 g/ml (Ô¨Ånal) phospho‚Äêp44/42 MAP kinase (Thr202/Try204) antibody, and incubate for 1 h at room temperature. 9. Aspirate primary antibody, wash once with blocking buffer, and incubate for 15 min at room temperature. 10. Aspirate and wash once with 100 l PBS and aspirate. 11. Add 50 l secondary antibody and stain; 10 g/ml (Ô¨Ånal) Alexa 488 goat anti‚Äêrabbit IgG and 2 g/ml (Ô¨Ånal) Hoechst 33342 dye in PBS and incubate for 1 h at room temperature in the dark. 12. Aspirate and wash once with 100 l blocking buffer and incubate for 10 min at room temperature. 13. Aspirate buffer and wash once with 100 l wash buffer. 14. Aspirate buffer, add 100 l of wash buffer, and seal plate. 15. Read plate on the ArrayScan.
ERK1/2 Activation Signal Window and Reproducibility

To evaluate the reproducibility of the ERK activation response in HeLa cells, cells were plated and on the following day are treated with the indicated doses of OSM or PMA in three independent experiments run on separate days (Fig. 6A and B). The EC50 for OSM‚Äêinduced ERK activation ranges from 0.1 to 0.22 ng/ml and produces on average an EC50 of 0.169 √Ü 0.062 ng/ml, indicating a reproducible assay (Fig. 6A). The EC50 for PMA‚Äêinduced ERK activation ranges from 0.81 to 0.95 ng/ml and produces, on average, an EC50 of 0.884 √Ü 0.068 ng/ml, indicating a reproducible assay (Fig. 6B). To evaluate the ability of the ERK activation response in HeLa cells to identify ERK pathway inhibitors, cells were plated and on the next day the indicated doses of the MEK1/2 inhibitor U0126 were added 15 min prior to the addition

408

measuring biological responses with automated microscopy

[22]

of 10 ng/ml OSM and cells were incubated for an additional 10 min (Fig. 6C). In three independent experiments, the IC50 for the MEK1/2 inhibitor U0126 ranged from 0.489 to 0.711 M and produced, on average, an IC50 of 0.616 √Ü 0.115 M. To further evaluate the robustness and reproducibility of the ERK activation response in HeLa cells, three full 96‚Äêwell plates were treated under the following conditions, one plate per condition: medium alone (green circles), 10 ng/ml OSM (red triangles), and 10 ng/ml OSM √æ 10 M staurosporin (blue squares)(Fig. 6D). The average Cytonuc difference for the media control plate was 71, and the average Cytonuc difference for the anisomycin‚Äêtreated control plate was 177, producing an average assay signal‚Äêto‚Äêbackground window of 2.49‚Äêfold. A comparison of medium control plate variability data to anisomycin‚Äêtreated plate variability data produced a Z factor of 0.54, indicating that the assay would be compatible with HTS (Zhang et al., 1999).
MAPK Pathway Inhibitor Test Cassette

To evaluate the three independent MAPK signaling pathway imaging assays that we had developed and to determine their ability to discriminate selectivity proÔ¨Åles across the MAPK family, we assembled a test cassette of known MAPK pathway inhibitors (Table I). In addition to Ô¨Åve ‚Äò‚Äòselective‚Äô‚Äô p38 inhibitors, we included the JNK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor SP 600125, the MEK‚Äê1/2 inhibitors UO126 and PD 98059, the PI3‚Äêkinase inhibitor wortmannin, and staurosporin as a nonselective kinase inhibitor. We also selected two activation stimuli for each MAPK pathway assay: anisomycin and TNF for the p38 pathway, anisomycin and IL‚Äê1 for the JNK pathway, and OSM and PMA for the ERK pathway (Table I). All Ô¨Åve p38 inhibitors produced IC50 values for inhibition of anisomycin‚Äê and TNF‚Äêinduced MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation <100 nM. UO126 and PD 98059, the MEK‚Äê1/2 inhibitors, produced IC50 values in the 20 to 39 M range for both activating stimuli, whereas the nonselective kinase inhibitor staurosporin produced submicromolar IC50 values for both stimuli (Table I). Neither the PI3‚Äêkinase inhibitor wortmannin nor the JNK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor SP 600125 inhibited anisomycin‚Äê or TNF‚Äêinduced MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation. Overall, the MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation assay appears exquisitively sensitive to p38 inhibitors relative to other kinase inhibitors. In the c‚ÄêJun activation assay, the JNK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor SP 600125 and staurosporin produced IC50 values of 8.6 and 1.4 M, respectively, with IL‚Äê1√ü as the stimulus , and IC50 values of 14 and 7.2 M, respectively, with anisomycin as the stimulus (Table I). Three of the Ô¨Åve ‚Äò‚Äòselective‚Äô‚Äô p38 inhibitors, the Merck p38 inhibitor, RWJ 68354, and SB203580, produced IC50 values between 20 and 40 M with anisomycin as the activating stimulus, whereas only the Merck

