p38 inhibitor and RWJ 68354 inhibited c‚ÄêJun activation by IL‚Äê1√ü. Two of the Ô¨Åve ‚Äò‚Äòselective‚Äô‚Äô p38 inhibitors, VX‚Äê745 and SB242235, did not inhibit c‚ÄêJun activation by either stimulus. Neither of the MEK‚Äê1/2 inhibitors UO126 and PD 98059 nor the PI3‚Äêkinase inhibitor wortmannin inhibited c‚ÄêJun activation by anisomycin, although U0126 inhibited IL‚Äê1√ü‚Äêinduced activation (Table I). Clearly the c‚ÄêJun activation assay was inhibited by the JNK‚Äê1/2 kinase inhibitor; however, it was also susceptible to three of the Ô¨Åve p38 inhibitors, albeit at >100‚Äêfold less sensitivity that the MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation p38 MAPK pathway assay. The MEK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor U0126 produced IC50 values in the 1 to 7 M range for both ERK activation stimuli, whereas the nonselective kinase inhibitor staurosporin produced nanomolar IC50 values for both stimuli, and the Merck p38 inhibitor produced IC50 values in the 11 to 12 M range for both stimuli (Table II). SB203580 produced an IC50 of 26 M with PMA as the activating stimulus, but failed to inhibit OSM‚Äêinduced ERK activation. None of the other compounds inhibited ERK activation by either stimulus: the MEK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor PD 98059, three of the ‚Äò‚Äòselective‚Äô‚Äô p38 inhibitors, VX‚Äê745, RWJ 68354, and SB242235, the PI3‚Äêkinase inhibitor wortmannin, and the JNK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor SP 600125 (Table I). The ERK activation assay was the least susceptible to inhibition by compounds that are reportedly selective for the other MAPK signaling pathways (Table I). Staurosporin is a potent inhibitor of numerous kinases in vitro that is active in many cell‚Äêbased assays. The ability of staurosporin to inhibit all three MAPK signaling pathways assays (Table I) is likely due to its ability to bind to the ATP‚Äêbinding sites of multiple kinases in these pathways. The Merck p38 inhibitor also produced IC50 values in all three assays, but the ability to inhibit the JNK and ERK signaling pathways (Table I) was likely due to the apparent cytotoxicity, or signiÔ¨Åcantly reduced adherence of the HeLa cells, observed at the two highest concentrations of the compound (Williams et al., 2006). Images revealed that there were much fewer cells in the Ô¨Åelds of view captured from wells treated with 50 and 16.6 M of the Merck p38 inhibitor compared to the 5.5 M dose, which produced obvious outliers in several cell number and morphology parameters derived by the image analysis algorithm (Williams et al., 2006). The high‚Äêcontent nature of image‚Äêderived data therefore provides additional information that may be a consequence of target inhibition or may be due to off‚Äêtarget effects of the compound. The Merck p38 inhibitor produced an IC50 $ 7‚Äì10 nM in the MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation p38 MAPK pathway assay and IC50 values of 20 and 10 M in the JNK and ERK signaling pathway assays, respectively. A number of the p38 inhibitors, including the Merck p38 inhibitor, have been withdrawn from clinical trials because of adverse toxicity proÔ¨Åles (English and Cobb, 2002; Fabbro et al., 2002; Noble et al., 2004; Regan et al., 2002).

