In contrast to staurosporin and the Merck p38 MAPK inhibitor, the PI3‚Äêkinase inhibitor wortmannin did not inhibit any of the three MAPK signaling pathway assays (Table I), and the JNK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor SP 600125 only inhibited the c‚ÄêJun activation assay, perhaps indicating some degree of MAPK pathway selectivity (Table I). The MEK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor UO126 produced IC50 values ranging between 1.2 and 6.9 M in the ERK activation assay and an IC50 of 44 M in the IL‚Äê1‚Äêinduced c‚ÄêJun activation assay. In contrast, the MEK‚Äê1/2 inhibitor PD 98059 did not inhibit either the c‚ÄêJun or the ERK activation assay. The MEK‚Äê1/2 inhibitors UO126 and PD 98059 produced IC50 values ranging between 25 and 39 M in the MK2‚Äê EGFP translocation p38 MAPK assay, perhaps indicating that ERK1/2 may be capable of phosphorylating MK2 as well as MK1 or perhaps reÔ¨Çecting the cross talk between the different modules of MAPK signaling pathways (Cowan and Storey, 2003; Garrington and Johnson, 1999). All Ô¨Åve p38 inhibitors produced IC50 values for inhibition of anisomycin‚Äê and TNF‚Äêinduced MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation <200 nM (Table I). As discussed

