earlier, the Merck p38 inhibitor also inhibited the c‚ÄêJun and ERK activation assays with IC50 values of 20 and 10 M, respectively, likely due to the apparent cytotoxicity at these concentrations interfering with the image analysis algorithm. The RWJ 68354 p38 inhibitor inhibited anisomycin‚Äê and TNF‚Äêinduced MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation with IC50 values between 74 and 87 nM and the c‚ÄêJun activation assay with IC50 values between 20 and 38 M. The SB203580 p38 inhibitor inhibited anisomycin‚Äê and TNF‚Äê induced MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation with IC50 values between 53 and 220 nM and the c‚ÄêJun and ERK activation assays with IC50 values of 41 and 26 M, respectively. In general, therefore, selective MAPK inhibitors exhibited pathway selectivity by producing signiÔ¨Åcantly lower IC50 values for their respective ERK, JNK, or p38 signaling pathway assays. However, each of the MAPK pathways assays was also susceptible to nonselective kinase inhibitors such as staurosporin and inhibitors that inhibit upstream MKKKs and MKKs in the MAPK signaling pathway, especially those involved in the cross talk between different modules of the MAPK signaling pathways.
p38 Inhibitor Hit Assessment

Williams et al. (2006) and Trask et al. (2006) described the development and optimization of the MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation assay and the subsequent use of this assay to screen a 32K kinase biased library to identify p38 MAPK inhibitors. As part of the follow‚Äêup hit assessment for the screen, selected hits and related structural analogs were proÔ¨Åled in the three MAPK signaling pathway assays described here (Table II). Eleven of the 16 hits and related analogs produced an IC50 in the anisomycin‚Äêinduced MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation assay: 4 in the submicromolar range, 5 in the 1 to 10 M range, and 2 at $14 M (Table II). Five of the 16 hits and related analogs produced an IC50 in the anisomycin‚Äêinduced c‚ÄêJun activation assay: 3 in the 1 to 10 M range, 1 at $18 M, and 1 at 38 M (Table II). None of the 16 hits and related analogs produced an IC50 in the OSM‚Äêinduced ERK activation assay (Table II). Most of the hits produced signiÔ¨Åcantly lower IC50 values in the MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation assay relative to the c‚ÄêJun activation assay, and 3 of the hit scaffolds identiÔ¨Åed in the MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation HCS were selected for p38a inhibitor hit‚Äêto‚Äêlead chemistry structure activity relationship (SAR).
p38a Inhibitor Profiling

To further evaluate the ability of the three MAPK signaling pathway assays to discriminate activity across these pathways, we compiled a set of

414

measuring biological responses with automated microscopy

[22]

40 compounds directed at p38 inhibition. All 40 compounds produced IC50 values in the p38 cell‚Äêbased MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation assay: 29 in the submicromolar range, 10 in the 1 to 5 M range, and 1 at $21.7 M (Table III). Three of the 40 tested produced IC50 values in the cell‚Äêbased ERK activation assay: 3 in the 30 to 40 M range (Table III), suggesting little or no interference with the ERK MAPK pathway. In contrast, 22 of the 40 p38 inhibitors also inhibited the c‚ÄêJun activation assay, albeit with signiÔ¨Åcantly less potency than in the MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation assay: 1 in the submicromolar range, 5 in the 1 to 10 M range, and 16 in the 10 to 40 M range (Table III). Although most of the compounds exhibited low nanomolar potency against p38 isoforms in vitro, a number of these compounds also exhibited submicromolar or low nanomolar potency against JNK isoforms in vitro (data not shown). In the majority of cases, however, despite exhibiting low to mid‚Äênanomolar potency in the MK2‚ÄêEGFP translocation assay, these mixed p38‚ÄêJNK inhibitors typically only produced 5 to 30 M potencies in the c‚ÄêJun activation assay. Because all three MAPK pathway assays were performed in the HeLa cell background, it is unlikely that differential cell permeability is contributing to the apparent differences in cellular potencies between mixed p38‚ÄêJNK inhibitors with similar in vitro potencies. In general, the apparent MAPK selectivity proÔ¨Åle from the in vitro kinase assays was reÔ¨Çected in the cell‚Äêbased MAPK assays; however, the apparent p38 selectivity of the compounds was typically more pronounced in the cell‚Äêbased assays.
JNK Inhibitor Profiling

To further characterize the selectivity of the three MAPK signaling pathway assays, a set of 40 JNK inhibitors was assembled (Table IV). Twenty‚Äêthree of the 40 compounds produced IC50 values in the c‚ÄêJun activation cell‚Äêbased assay: 4 in the sub‚Äêmicromolar range, 3 in the 1 to 10 M range, and 16 in the 10 to 40 M range (Table IV). However, despite exhibiting potencies in the mid‚Äênanomolar or sub‚Äêmicromolar IC50 values in the JNK in vitro kinase assays (data not shown), with only four exceptions the compounds typically produced cellular activity in the 5 to 40 M range. Fifteen of the 40 tested also produced IC50 values in the cell‚Äêbased ERK activation assay: 3 in the 1 to 10 M range and 12 in the 10 to 40 M range (Table IV). The ERK MAPK module responds primarily to growth factors and mitogens and is involved in the regulation of cell division, migration, and survival (Cowan and Storey, 2003; Garrington and Johnson, 1999; Johnson and Lapadat, 2002), and inhibition of this pathway may have an adverse effect that could impact the therapeutic index of these JNK inhibitors. Conversely, there appears to be relatively little interference of the p38 MAPK signaling

